items.abstract:
<jats:p>Let hom(<jats:italic>G</jats:italic>) denote the size of the largest clique or independent set of a graph <jats:italic>G</jats:italic>. In 2007, Bukh and Sudakov proved that every <jats:italic>n</jats:italic>-vertex graph <jats:italic>G</jats:italic> with hom(<jats:italic>G</jats:italic>) = <jats:italic>O</jats:italic>(log<jats:italic>n</jats:italic>) contains an induced subgraph with Ω(<jats:italic>n</jats:italic>
               <jats:sup>1/2</jats:sup>) distinct degrees, and raised the question of deciding whether an analogous result holds for every <jats:italic>n</jats:italic>-vertex graph <jats:italic>G</jats:italic> with hom(<jats:italic>G</jats:italic>) = <jats:italic>O</jats:italic>(<jats:italic>n<jats:sup>ϵ</jats:sup>
               </jats:italic>), where <jats:italic>ϵ</jats:italic> &gt; 0 is a fixed constant. Here, we answer their question in the affirmative and show that every graph <jats:italic>G</jats:italic> on <jats:italic>n</jats:italic> vertices contains an induced subgraph with Ω((<jats:italic>n</jats:italic>/hom(<jats:italic>G</jats:italic>))<jats:sup>1/2</jats:sup>) distinct degrees. We also prove a stronger result for graphs with large cliques or independent sets and show, for any fixed <jats:italic>k</jats:italic> ∈ ℕ, that if an <jats:italic>n</jats:italic>-vertex graph <jats:italic>G</jats:italic> contains no induced subgraph with <jats:italic>k</jats:italic> distinct degrees, then hom(<jats:italic>G</jats:italic>)⩾<jats:italic>n</jats:italic>/(<jats:italic>k</jats:italic> − 1) − <jats:italic>o</jats:italic>(<jats:italic>n</jats:italic>); this bound is essentially best possible.</jats:p>
